What is a Dataset?

A dataset is a collection of data usually presented in tabular (table) form. Each dataset is made up of both rows and columns and contains information regarding a specific subject matter.

The dataset will look something like this:


Observations (Rows)

A dataset contains many observations which are represented by rows in the table. Examples of observations (rows) in a dataset could be:

  • People
  • Games
  • Houses
  • Cars


Variables (Columns)

A dataset contains many variables which are represented by columns in the table. Each column corresponds to a specific piece of information regarding that observation. Examples of variables (columns) could be:

  • Age of the person
  • Sales of the video game
  • Price of the house
  • Weight of the car


Types of Variables

There are many different types of variables that we will be working with:

  • Identification Variables: Variables that are used to identify results - a single value for every observations.
    • Examples: Social Security Number, Employee ID Number, Observation Number
  • Continuous Variables: Variables that can have an infinite number of values.
    • Examples: Weight, Price, Time
  • Categorical Variables: Variables that have values that can be grouped into categories.
    • Nominal: 2 or more categories but no order (Examples: Types of property, States)
    • Binary: Only 2 categories (Examples: Male/Female, Yes/No, 0/1)
    • Ordinal: 2 or more categories that have an order (Examples: Low/Medium/High, Poor/Average/Good)


Target & Predictor Variables

We also want to identify our target (dependent) variable and predictor (independent) variables. Our target variable is the thing we are trying to predict, while our predictor variables are the variables we are using to predict the target.

What is a Predictive Model?

As part of the analysis we will be performing on your dataset, we will be building something called a predictive model. A predictive model is taking a bunch of variables and data about a certain subject and predicting outcomes based on that data. Some examples include:

  • Predicting the sales of iPhones based on customer characteristics
  • Predicting if a customer is likely to cancel Netflix or not based on viewer characteristics
  • Predicting the price of a car based on economic chracteristics
  • Predicting the number of Super Bowl viewers based on the American public characteristics
  • Predicting if an email is spam or not based on word characteristics

A very simple predictive model is a model with one variable. This may be more familiar to you if we write it out in formula form: \[y = mx + b \]

In statistics, we write this same formula as: \[y = \beta_1x_1 + \beta_0 \] In this formula, \(\beta_o\) is the y-intercept just as \(b\) is above. \(\beta_1\) is the slope of the line just as \(m\) is in the above formula.

Now, let’s say we want to predict someone’s weight based on their height (a one variable predictive model). We have plotted out the observations we have in our data as shown below:


We have fit a predictive model to the data (straight line) and we know the parameter estimates (slope & y-intercept) as well. We can write out this predictive model as: \[Predicted Weight = 3.899(height) + (-143) \]

We can now use this formula to predict other observations that weren’t in our dataset. Some examples:

  • Height of 5 ft person (60 inches): 90.94 lbs
  • Height of 5 1/2 ft person (66 inches): 114.334 lbs
  • Height of 6 ft person (72 inches): 137.728 lbs
  • Height of 6 1/2 ft person (78 inches): 161.122 lbs

DISCLAIMER: This is fake data from the internet.

If we have more than one variable in our predictive model, we continue to add \(\beta_n\) terms to the model such as this: \[y = \beta_1x_1 + \beta_2x_2 + \beta_3x_3 + ... + \beta_nx_n + \beta_0 \]

This is further discussed below in the interpretation section.


What If We Didn’t Build a Predictive Model?

Using an example from above, what if we wanted to predict the sales of iPhones but didn’t want to build a predictive model? One thing we could do is randomly guess the sales. This mostly likely wouldn’t result in very good predictions. Another thing we could do which would be better than a random guess is to use the mean or median as our prediction. While not everyone in our dataset may be close to the mean or median, those values should be a lot closer than our random guess. As you will see below in our Model Performance section, we will calculate statistics for predictions based off of a random guess, the mean, the median, and finally our predictive model. This will hopefully allow you to see the importance of a predictive model! Until then, let’s keep building our predictive model…


Partition Data

When building a predictive model, we build the model on only part of the dataset. This is know as the Training Data. We typically use 60-70% of the entire dataset as the Training Data. That leaves 30-40% of the dataset remaining for us to test our predictive model on. We call this our Validation Data.

As an example of this concept, let’s say we wanted to predict the sale of yearbooks at BHS. We have information about every high school student and after splitting the dataset, we will use the training data to build this model. We can then test our model on the remaining students (validation) data. An important part of statistics and this type of analysis is to calculate how accurate your model was in predicting. In this example, we know what our model predicted for yearbook sales of the students in the validation data. But, we also know what the real sales were and can calculate how much error our model produced.


Create Training & Validation Data

Let’s split your dataset into training and validation data. Copy and paste the following code into your R Script and run it.

## Step 7: Splitting your dataset into 60% training and 40% validation ##
set.seed(10)
p60 <- quantile(All_Data$sim,0.6)
Training_Data <- All_Data[which(All_Data$sim <= p60),]
Validation_Data <- All_Data[which(All_Data$sim > p60),]


EDA

Before we start model building, it’s important to do Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA). EDA helps us look at the relationships in the data before we start modeling. It may reveal patterns that we didn’t know existed before and could help with our interpretation of the model later. EDA can involve things such as:

  • Deciles - How spread out are the values in each variable?
  • Frequencies - For the categorical variables, do the levels of those variables make sense and are there adequate number of observations in each level?
  • Plots - Are there patterns in the data that we don’t expect?
  • Correlations - How correlated are the variables in our dataset?

Correlations

Correlation is a measure of how strongly pairs of variables are related to each other. A correlation can range between -1 and +1 with -1 meaning perfect negative correlation, 0 meaning no correlation, and + 1 meaning perfect positive correlation. A perfect positive or negative correlation would result in a straight line between variables. Here are a few examples:




Let’s play a quick game of guess the correlation! http://www.rossmanchance.com/applets/GuessCorrelation.html

Variable Selection

Our datasets can contain hundreds if not thousands of variables for each observation. We never want to use all the variables to model with for these reasons:

  • Many of the variables will be correlated. As discussed in the last section, correlated variables can mess up our interpretation of the model.
  • Risk of overfitting. When we build a model with too many variables, we may risk fitting our model (the line) perfectly through our training dataset. But, then we go to validate our model and we calculate a huge error because the model is perfectly built for the training data, but not for any other dataset. It doesn’t generalize well.
  • Difficult to interpret. If there are too many variables in our model, it can be very difficult to interpret them and make sense of your model.

To help us narrow down the variables that should make it into our model, we use something called variable selection. We will look at one type when building our model - forward selection.


Forward Selection

With this technique, we start with no variables in the model and add variables to the model one at a time. At each step, each variable that is not already in the model is tested for inclusion in the model. The most significant of these variables (based on a certain criteria) is added to the model, so long as the variable meets the criteria significance you have set.

In this case, we are going to perform forward selection based on the AIC criteria. Copy, paste, and run the following code to perform forward selection for your data:

## Step 17: Fitting a model using forward selection ##
null = lm(mpg_highway~1, data=Training_Data)


full = lm(mpg_highway~engine_size + cylinders + horsepower + weight + wheelbase + length + factor(car) + factor(suv) + factor(from_asia) + factor(from_europe) + factor(from_usa) + sim,data=Training_Data)


Fit_Forward = step(null, scope=list(lower=null, upper=full), direction="forward")

Fitting Final Regression Model

We are going to fit our final regression model using the results from forward selection.

Copy, paste, and run the following code to fit your model:

## Step 19: Fitting the final regression model ##

Model Performance

In order to measure how well our model is performing against our validation data, there are lots of different statistics we could look at. We are going to focus on two different stats - Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) and R-Squared.


MAPE

Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) is a measure of prediction accuracy. It is defined as:

\[MAPE=\frac{1}{n} \sum_{t=1}^n \left\lvert{\frac{Actual_t - Predicted_t}{Actual_t}}\right\rvert * 100\] where: n = # of observations (in this case in our validation data) and t = observation #.


MAPE for Predictions from Your Predictive Model

Copy, paste, and run the following code to calculate the MAPE for your predictive model against the validation data:

## Step 21: Calculating MAPE from your predictive model ##
count_obs_val <- nrow(Validation_Predictions)
Inside_val <- abs((Validation_Predictions$mpg_highway - Validation_Predictions$val_predict)/Validation_Predictions$mpg_highway)
MAPE_val <- ((1/count_obs_val)*sum(Inside_val))*100
MAPE_val
[1] 7.49

Interpreting the P-Values

The p-value for each term tests the null hypothesis that the coefficient is equal to zero (has no effect in the model). A low p-value (< 0.05) indicates that you can reject the null hypothesis. In other words, a predictor that has a low p-value is likely to be a meaningful additional to your model because changes in the predictor’s value are related to changes in the target variable.

Interpreting the beta coefficients

We also want to interpret our beta coefficients that the model outputs. Regression beta coefficients represent the mean change in the target variable for a one unit change in the predictor variable while holding all other predictor variables in the model constant. Remember from a few sections ago, our beta coefficients are like our “slope” terms or our \(\beta_n\) terms. How do we interpret the coefficients in the dataset?

## Step 27: How do we interpret the coefficients in your dataset?  ##

## * weight - The Highway MPG will decrease by 0.002358 if I increase the weight of the car by 1 pound.

## * horsepower - The Highway MPG will decrease by 0.022803 if I increase the car's horsepower by 1 unit.

## * factor(car)Yes - Relative to the base category (No), the Highway MPG will increase by 4.190985 if I drive a car. Another way of saying this is driving a car will increase the Highway MPG by 4.190985 compared to driving an SUV or a truck. 

## * engine_size - The Highway MPG will decrease by 0.814026 if I increase the car's engine size by 1 unit.


Writing out the model formula

Going back to our “What is a Predictive Model?” section, we learned that we can write out our regression formula similarly to the slope of a line formula (y = mx + b). Now that we have our final model with beta coefficients, we can write out that formula using the principles we learned earlier. Remember the generic equation of a regression model is this:

\[y = \beta_1x_1 + \beta_2x_2 + \beta_3x_3 + ... + \beta_nx_n + \beta_0 \]

We can fill in our beta coefficients and x’s using our Sample data as: \[ \begin{align} Predicted Highway MPG = -0.002358(weight) - 0.022803(horsepower) + 4.190985(car) \\ - 0.814026(enginesize) + 39.336603 \end{align} \]

Using the formula to predict another observation

Another thing we can do is use our model to predict new observations. For example, let’s say I’m looking to buy a new car and want to predict what the car’s highway gas mileage will be. These are the specifications of the new car:

  • It’s a car (not an SUV or Truck)

  • It weighs 2800 pounds

  • It is not made in the USA

  • It has a wheelbase of 100

  • It has a horsepower of 225

  • It has an engine size of 3

Using these specifications, what will the highway miles per gallon be? To solve this, we can plug in these new specifications into our formula from above like so:

\[ \begin{align} Predicted Highway MPG = -0.002358(2800) - 0.022803(225) + 4.190985(1) \\ - 0.814026(3) + 39.336603 \end{align} \]

\[Predicted Highway MPG = 29.35244 \] We pull out our calculator to solve the equation and see that the Predicted Highway Miles Per Gallon of our new car is 29.35244.
